M. TULH CICERONIS IN O. VERREM ACTIO SECUNDA

LIB. V cc. 61-66

The effect of Cicero's opening address (Aetio I) on court and people was such that the presiding praetor adj ourned the court. Hortensius, realizing that the plan for postponement was defeated and that his client had no chance of escape on a fair trial, threw up the case and Verres went into exile.

Actio II was never presented orally in court, but in it Cicero has assembled the facts on which he rested his case. It is perhaps the most complete and terrible arraigmnent of a corrupt and oppressive ruler ever presented. Burke's impeachment of Warren- Hastings is the nearest modern parallel, and no doubt many features of it were suggested by this—for Burke drew much of his inspiration as an orator from the classice.
